    "summary": "Objection: \"character\" is too vague to constrain interpretation",
    "content": "**Strongest objection to \"character\":** It is too vague to constrain the reader's interpretation.\n\n\"All things have their character\" -- the English reader hears something like \"all things have their distinctive quality\" or \"all things have a personality.\" This is true but empty. It does not direct the reader toward the author's specific meaning: *the set of properties inductively assembled from phenomena and retroactively imposed as definitional*. \"Character\" is compatible with the author's meaning but does not *point toward* it. It is a blank check the reader fills in with whatever they already think.\n\nCompare: \"All things have their De (the defining characteristics that make a thing what it is)\" -- now the reader has a specific concept. Then bare \"De\" in running text carries that concept forward. Bare \"character\" in running text carries... vagueness forward.\n\nIf the choice is between \"character\" and \"De,\" the question is: do you want a word the reader thinks they already understand (but fills with the wrong content), or a word they know they don't understand (and must learn from the text)? For a term this philosophically specific, the second is safer."
